the possibilities for responding to the use and abuse of public spaces and explores how a culture might memorialize its historical figures and events in ways that are beneficial to all its members.Written in Stone is a meditation on how national cultures have been or may yet be defined through the deployment of public monuments. It adds a thoughtful and crucial voice into debates surrounding historical accuracy and representation, and will be welcomed by the many readers concerned with such issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aFlagsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aMonumentsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aMulticulturalismzUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aConfederate monuments. 4aConfederate symbols. 4aMonument Avenue Richmond. 4acollective memory. 4acommemorative monuments. 4amemorial statues. 4apublic art. 4apublic monuments. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Physical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822399995zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822399995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822399995.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles